library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
spec(districts)

cols(
  system = col_double(),
  system_name = col_character(),
  alg_1 = col_double(),
  alg_2 = col_double(),
  bio = col_double(),
  chem = col_double(),
  ela = col_double(),
  eng_1 = col_double(),
  eng_2 = col_double(),
  eng_3 = col_double(),
  math = col_double(),
  science = col_double(),
  enrollment = col_double(),
  black = col_double(),
  hispanic = col_double(),
  native = col_double(),
  el = col_double(),
  swd = col_double(),
  ed = col_double(),
  expenditures = col_double(),
  act_composite = col_double(),
  chronic_abs = col_double(),
  suspended = col_double(),
  expelled = col_double(),
  grad = col_double(),
  dropout = col_double(),
  region = col_character()
)
# 1) Clean and explore data using tidyverse verbs, e.g. arrange, filter, mutate, and select.
# 2) Calculate descriptive statistics, including finding aggregate values by group.
regional_spending <- districts %>% 
  group_by(region, system_name) %>% 
  summarize(median_reg_spending = median(expenditures))

`summarise()` has grouped output by 'region'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(regional_act,
       aes(x = region,
           y = median_reg_act,
           color = region)) +
  geom_point()
